&gt; That was my first thought as well, and the solution I 
&gt; currently have.  But
&gt; consider this......
&gt; 
&gt; You can instantiate a JTextField 5 different ways and a 
&gt; JTextArea 6.  So
&gt; using the system that (I think) we agree is the way to go we 
&gt; would have to
&gt; subclass AbstractEnhancedTextfieldTest 5 times for JTextField 
&gt; and 6 times
&gt; for JTextArea.  And in each subclass instantiate the Text Area/Field
&gt; differently.  E.g.
&gt; 	
&gt; 	// sub class one
&gt; 	new JTextArea()
&gt; 
&gt; 	//sub class two
&gt; 	new JTextArea(&quot;Second Type Of Constructor&quot;)
&gt; 
&gt; 	// etc
&gt; 
&gt; However you look at it you have to extend 
&gt; AbstractEnhancedTextfieldTest N
&gt; times, where N equals the possible number of constructors 
&gt; (for the different
&gt; objects) their are.  I wanted to have N number of statements 
&gt; in one class
&gt; (the Test Client) rather than N number of very &#39;thin&#39; 
&gt; subclasses.  In the
&gt; end I don&#39;t suppose it matters, the behaviour would be the same.
&gt; 
&gt; I suppose what I was after was, in pseudo code, was something 
&gt; like this:
&gt; 
&gt; 	suite.addTestSuite(MyTestClass.class)
&gt; 		where component = new TextComponent()
&gt; 
&gt; 	suite.addTestSuite(MyTestClass.class)
&gt; 		where component = new TextComponent(&quot;String&quot;)
&gt; 
&gt; 	suite.addTestSuite(MyTestClass.class)
&gt; 		where component = new TextComponent(myDocument)		
&gt; 
&gt; 	etc etc etc
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks for all the quick responses everyone.
&gt; 
&gt; James
